{{Quote|I knew that I needed someone who could convey evil. But in addition, I needed someone to bring stature, strength, and wisdom to the role. There was no doubt in my mind that Christopher Lee was the right person.|George Lucas, on casting Christopher Lee as Count Dooku|<ref name="Christopher Lee biography">{{BookCite|author=Rigby, Jonathan|container=Foreword|title=Christopher Lee: The Authorized Screen History|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn|date=2001|isbn=1903111110}}</ref>}}
[[Wikipedia:Knight Bachelor|Sir]] '''Christopher Frank Carandini Lee''' [[Wikipedia:Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Wikipedia:Venerable Order of Saint John|CStJ]] ([[May 27]], [[1920s#1922|1922]] &ndash; [[June 7]], [[2015]]) was the actor who played [[Count of Serenno|Count]] [[Dooku]], also named [[Darth]] Tyranus, in the [[2002]] film [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']] and the [[2005]] film [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']], and he performed the same character's voice in the [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' film]] of [[2008]].

Lee was known for his work in horror films produced by [[Wikipedia:Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Studios]] in collaboration with [[Peter Cushing]], who played [[Grand Moff]] [[Wilhuff Tarkin|Tarkin]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']],<ref name="YouTube">{{YouTube|video=mdrE32cyKC8|text=Star Wars Interview Christopher Lee (Count Dooku) on Peter Cushing (Tarkin)|channel=channel/UCcTBalBac0W2A1Xhf8AmENQ|name=Mike magic|quote=This wonderful name, Grand Moff Tarkin.|archivedate=20200829203940}}</ref> playing the villain [[Wikipedia:Francisco Scaramanga|Francisco Scaramanga]] in the Roger Moore James Bond film [[Wikipedia:The Man With the Golden Gun|''The Man With the Golden Gun'']], portraying Pakistan's founder [[Wikipedia:Muhammad Ali Jinnah|Muhammad Ali Jinnah]] in the 1998 film [[Wikipedia:Jinnah (film)|''Jinnah'']], and playing the wizard Saruman in [[Wikipedia:The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]].<ref name="TF">{{WebCite|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/the_total_film_interview__christopher_lee|text=The Total Film Interview - Christopher Lee|author=Robert Sellers|date=2005-05-01|work=[[Wikipedia:Total Film|''Total Film'']]|archivedate=20070612192345|nolive=1}}</ref> On [[June 13]], [[2009]], Lee was knighted in the Queen's Birthday Honours List.<ref name="BBC">{{WebCite|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8096881.stm|text=Veteran horror actor Lee knighted|date=2009-06-12|work=[[Wikipedia:BBC News|BBC News]]|archivedate=20190406231438}}</ref>

==Biography==
[[File:Dooku-CGSWG.png|thumb|right|250px|Sir Christopher Lee as Count Dooku]]
Sir Christopher Lee portrayed the [[Serennian]] [[Count]] [[Dooku]] in [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']]<ref name="Clones">{{Film|II}}</ref> and [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']].<ref name="Revenge">{{Film|III}}</ref> Lee returned to his role as Dooku in the animated film [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'']], doing the voice of Count Dooku.<ref name="Clone Wars Film">[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' film]]</ref>

Sir Christopher Lee died at the age of 93 on [[June 7]], [[2015]], after being hospitalized for respiratory problems from heart failure.<ref name="death" />

Lee's niece, [[Harriet Walter]], appeared in [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']] as [[Doctor]] [[Harter Kalonia]].<ref name="Awaken">{{Film|VII}}</ref>

